{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bd5f2cf3-74ad-4eb7-bccb-d9bd908773d3","content":"\n\nIn your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Created\");\n    window.Activated     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Activated\");\n    window.Deactivated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Deactivated\");\n    window.Stopped       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Stopped\");\n    window.Resumed       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Resumed\");\n    window.Destroying    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Destroying\");\n    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Backgrounding\");\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Typical transition order:**\n\n| Scenario | Events |\n|---|---|\n| App launch | `Created → Activated` |\n| Backgrounded | `Deactivated → Stopped` |\n| Resumed | `Resumed → Activated` |\n| Closed | `Deactivated → Stopped → Destroying` |\n\n> **Note:** `Backgrounding` is iOS/Mac Catalyst only — use it to save state before the OS may terminate the app. On Android/Windows it won't fire.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0f58b954-068c-4d3a-93ec-c1bfb48a25fa","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI Window lifecycle events and how to subscribe to them for logging/debugging. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI, so I can answer directly without needing to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":418},"id":"499e1dca-ab30-44ae-98a0-661dae324642","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:39:56.758Z","parentId":"feda43c8-e359-4d64-8989-d9bc5886c0b7"}
